{"/service/ndnp/sdhi/batch_sdhi_grenada_ver01/data/sn99062034/00279523246/1908051201/0811.xml":{"full_text":"OKLftHDMAjORKAQU\nDestructive Wind Storms Sweep\nOver Four Counties.\nSEVEN VILLAGES WIPED OUT\nMany Pirwm Known to Have Been\nInjured and Number Are Reported\nKilled\u2014Section Devastated Isolated\nand Thinly Populated.\nWoodward, Ok la., May\nSeven\n:1\u00a7^-A\nvillages\n\u00abc\nCession of tornadoes swept over the\ndistrict lying two miles southwest,\niouth and southeast of Woodward.\nSeveral small Isolated villages, all off\nthe railroad and without telegraphic\ncommunication, are reported de\n\u2022troyed, many persons have been in\njured and a number are reported\nkilled.\nare reported to have\niuffwrud damage more or loss severe,\nhey are Graud, Arnett, Vicl, Mutual,\nSstolle, Cooley and Richmond. At\n\u2022ach place casualties are Bald to have\nresulted. The known casualties are:\nAt Arnett Hale, killed halt\na dozen persons Injured, one fatally.\nAt Vlclt\u2014 Hauser, physician,\nUatally injured.\nAt Mutual\u2014Arthur Blbel, his wife\nand several others were seriously In\nftired.\nGrand, the county seat of Elite\nfeounty, is said to have been wholly\nwrecked. The towns of Estelle, Coo\ntoy and Richmond also are reported\nto have been devastated.\nAt Little Robe, fifty-five miles south\nWest of Woodward, Mrs. J. K. Hale\nwas killed.\nIn the vicinity of Arnett O. E. Null\nfund daughter were caught In the\nUtorm while driving. They escaped\nInjury, but their team was killed.\nThe little town of Cestos, Dewey\nfcounty, also is reported wiped ofT the\nmap.\nThe villages where the damage is\nreported are all small places. Grand\nIs the largest of the seven and it has\nonly a few hundred inhabitants.\nThe Bcene of the tornadoes is the\nnorthwest corner of the old border of\nOklahoma, close to the Texas and\nKansas state lines. As far as learned\nit traversed four counties and covered\na distance of Beventy-flve miles.\nTO RESTORE PROSPERITY.\nAaeoeiation Asks President's Aid In\nFurthering Plans.\nWashington, May 12.\u2014A committee\nfrom the National Prosperity associa\ntlon of St. IxjuIs called on President\nRoosevelt to urge his aid In further\nIng their plans for encouraging tin\nreturn of prosperity throughout th\ncountry. The committee found th\npresident cordial in his treatment an\nfrank in his expressions of willing\nnees to aid them In every way pos\nBible. A short speech was made by\nE. C. Simmons, chairman of the ex\necutlve committee of the association\nwhioh was responded to by the presi\ndent. Other members of the commit\ntee were F. G. Wade, Kdward Devory\nF. B. Wlberg, J. E. Smith, W. K. Bix\nfcy, Murray Carleton, George A. Meyer\nand Jackson Johnson.\nMOUNTED GIRLS AS ESCORT.\nFifty Louisiana Beauties In Red Stock\ning* to Attend Governor.\nClad in red silk stockings and mount\ned astride coal black horses, fifty of\nthe prettiest girls in Louisiana, twenty\nfive blonds and twenty-five brunettes,\nwill participate in a few days at Baton\nRouge in the inauguration of Governor\nJared Y. Sanders.\nThe girls were selected by Miss Mat\ntie McGrath, president of the Louisi\nana division of the Daughters of the\nConfederacy, who wanted the Btate's\nrepresentative beauties to pay tribute\nto the \"reform\" Democratic governor.\nMiss McGrath was an earnest support\ner of Sanders during his campaign and\nwants to celebrate the victory with a\nreal thriller.\nThe girls will be attired In white\nfrocks of dlmsy gauze with red hats.\nEach beauty will be carefully drilled\nIn horsemanship before she Is allowed\nto appear publicly on a charger.\nMuffler For Guns.\nA yotm* Norwegian of Wefeeeter,\nMass., has Invented a nmtHer for al'\nkinds of guns which makes them noise\nlees. An ambition to shoot bothersome\ncats without his nelghlwrs knowing\nthe origin of the shots brought about\nthis result. The muffler is a simple\npiece of rectangular steel two inches\nlong, fitted over the end of the gun.\nII Weighs only ten ounces.\nEditor Joseph Leicht Dftttt.\nWinona, Minn., May 11.\u2014A cable\ngram received here from Cherbourg,\nFrance, announces the death on the\nsteamer Lutxon of pneumonia of Jos\neph Leicht of tbiB city, who left here\nrecently for Europe for his health.\nThe body has been landed at Cher\nbourg awaiting instructions. Mr.\nLeicht founded the West licher-Herold\nIn this city about twenty-five years\nMP-\nPolish Schools Closed.\nICSelce, Uu-fian Poland, May 11.\u2014\nOn account of ilie recent assassination\nof Alana-'iolt', superintendent o!\nschools NNjUo, the governor gen\neral has (l.Htail all the private Polish\nschools in iLU province.\nVOTE TO GO ON STRIKE.\nStreet Car Employes Insist on the\n\"Closed\" Shop.\nChicago, May 12\u2014The strike vote\ntakon by the North and West Side\nstreet car men resulted in a prac\ntically unanimous vote In favor of a\nwalkout. The balloting marked the\nlargest vote ever cast in the history\nof the Street Car Men's union In Chi\ncago. Approximately 4,500 men, mem\nbers of division No. 241, embracing\nthe men employed on the North and\nWest Side street car lines, voted. Of\nthat, number fewer than 200 votes\nwere cast against a strike.\nThe matter now goes to a meeting\nof the union for further action.\nThe question of \"closed\" or \"open\"\nshop is the j\u00bboint around which the\n\u2022ntire difficulty revolves.\nBURKE WAS NOT THEM.\nHad\nBmii\nInvited to Addrcw ChlMO*\nManufacturers.\nChicago, May 11.\u2014-Four hundred dis\nappointed manufacturers sat at lunch\neon at the Grand Pacific hotel on the\nfailure of Governor John Burko of\nNorth Dakota to appear with his ad\ndress.\nIt was planned as a \"good cheer\"\nluncheon for the purpose of restoring\nconfidence and renewing prosperity.\nThe \"good cheer\" was unexpectedly\nput to flight by the non-appearance of\nthe speaker.\nTwo hours after the meeting b\u00bb\nadjourned Governor Burke strolled\ninto the hotel and aBked for a room.\n\"Why, the manufacturers have been\nlooking for you in every place,\" said\nthe clerk. \"You were to make a\nspeech, were you not?\"\n\"Yes,\" replied the governor, \"In the\nevening and 1 have a nice apeech all\nready in my grip.\"\nWhen told that the meeting had\nbeen held Governor Hurke opened his\ngrip, looked at the speech fondly and\nthen remarked:\n'When docB the Mxt traio leare for\nWashington\nAn examination of the correspond\nence Inviting the governor to make a\nspeech revealed the faot that all of\nthe letters used the word luncheon\nwithout naming the time of day\nSuperintendent Killed.\nMarietta, O., May 11.\u2014Superinten\ndent Joseph Young of the county in\nhrtuary, injured in an explosion and\nAre which destroyed a portion of that\nInstitution, is dead. His body was\nburned and bis right leg was shattered\nby jumping from a window. The loss\nis $3,000. Several of the 200 inmates\nsustained slight injuries. After a\ntemporary panic the inmates orga\nnized a fire brigade and saved the\nbuilding.\nBlehep Brent Undeolded.\nWashington, May 11.\u2014Bishop fh-eai\nof the Philippine islands, who recent\nly was elected bishop of Wauhiugtuii\nin succession to the late Bishop Sat\nterlee, has cabled the officials of the\nconference here that he now has the\ncall under consideration, but that he\nis not yet clear as to whether his duty\nrequires a continuance of his work In\nthe Philippines or the acceptance of\nthe call to this diocese.\nBRIEF BITS OF NEWS.\nSir Alexander Condle Stephen, K\nC., M. G., who was a groom in wait tug\nto the king, Is dead. He waa born In\n1850.\nBy a vote of 34 to tfee senate In\ncreased from $500,000 to $1,000,000 the\nmiscellaneous appropriation for the\nforestry service to be used in th*\nconstruction of roads, fire lanee, tele\nphone lines, etc.\nMARKET QUOTATIONS.\nMinneapolis Wheat.\nMinneapolis, May 11.\u2014Wheat\u2014May,\nfl.08Vfe July. $1.06% Sept., 9l%du\n91 Vic. On track\u2014No. 1 hard, $1.11\nNo. 1 Northern, $1.09 No. 2 Northern.\n$1.06^1.07^4 No. 3 Northern, Mcfr\n$1.04.\n\u2022t. Paul Union Stook Yard\u00ae.\nSt. Paul, May 11.\u2014Cattle\u2014Good to\nchoice steers, $0.00(56-75 fair to good\n$5.00^ 5.75 good to choice cows and\nheifers, $4.&0@5.50 veals, $3.76ti5 2B\nHogs\u2014$5.30(fi 5.40. Sheep\u2014Wethers\n$5.25 good to choice lambs, $G.2o$\n6 30.\nDuluth Wheat and Flax.\nDuluth, May 11.\u2014Wheat\u2014To. arrive\nand on track\u2014No. 1 hard, $1.10\u00bb% No,\n1 Northern, $1.08% \u00a91.08* No.\nNorthern, $1.04% 104% Mfey, $1.\n06% July. $1.06% Sept., 92%\u00ab. Flax\n\u2014To arrive and on track, $1.22%\nMay, $1.22 July, $1.23% Sept, $1.\n24% Oct., $1.23%.\nChicago Union Stock Yard*.\nChicago, May 11.\u2014Cattle\u2014Be^Tee,\n$4.80\u00a97.30 Texans, $4.70^5.60 West\nern cattle, $4.G5(t6.00 stockers and\nfeeders. J3.70(ii 5.70 cows and hoifera,\n$C.50ju 6.70 calves, $4.75(jj 6.25. Hogs\n\u2014Light, $5.30\u00a3fr.ft5 mixed, $5.30\n5-67\nMj\nheary, $5.25& 5.65 rough,\n5.40 good to choice heavy,\n$5.45(1/5.66 pigs, $4.60(26.25. Sheep,\n$4.00 6.10 yearling#, $6.M\u00a9\u00ab.80\nIambs, $5.&0#7.65.\nChicago Grain and Provisions.\nChicago, May 11.\u2014Wheat\u2014May,'\n$1.01 July, 90-14 Tr90Tie Sept., 86%c\nDec., 87V*e. Corn\u2014May, 71T\u00bbo July,\n63%c Sept., 62Vfcc Dec., 64%c.\nOats\u2014May, old, 55c May, 53c July,\nold, 47c July, 45%c Sept., 37H\u00ae\nB7%c. Pork\u2014May, $18.42M\u00bb: July.\n$13.67Vfe ft 13.60 Sept., $13.82li. But\nter\u2014Creameries, lStft)\u00a33c dairies, 18\n22c.\nEsks\u201415c.\nPoultry\u2014Turkeys,\n14c chlckeus, lfo broUenC.pw\niocen, $3.Qu'5 6.M.\nTOUR FQBJOBfflLT\nWhy\nPresident Plans to\nSpend\nTwo Years Abroad.\nWISHES TAFT TO BE FREE.\nHe Would Be Beyond the Reaeli Of\nAny Who Might Seek His Influence\nWith the Secretary if Elected His\nSuccessor\u2014Hope* to Hunt in African\nWilds.\nUnless there is a change In his pres\nent intentions President Itoosevelt will\nleave the United States soon after the\nInauguration of his successor on March\n4 next and will not return for two\nyears. There have been several reports\nin the last few months regarding the\nplans of Mr. Itoosevelt for the disposi\ntion of his time after his retirement\nfrom the presidency. None of them\nhas beeu nutborltative. It Is possible\nnow, however, says a Washington spe\nclal dispatch to the New York Times,\nto make a positive statement so far as\nthe present plans of the president are\nconcerned.\nA considerable part of the two years\nwhich he purposes to spend abroad\nwill le devoted by Mr. Roosevelt to\nthe hunting of big game. He Is likely\nto go first to Africa. Recently he had\na long conversation with a man who\nhas spent much time In hunting in\nAfrica, and the president was Intense\nly Interested In the first hand account\nof the sport which he received. He\nfeels that he has earned the right to\nput in a portion of his time In the\nsport which most appeals to him\nWhere he will go besides Africa has\nnot yet leen considered.\nThe president proposes to spend tw\nyears awny from the United States for\ntwo reasons. Rest and the reereatioi\nof hunting are only the minor ones\nHe Intends to put himself beyond th\nreach of those persons who would In\nevltably seek, If he were within reach,\nto use his Influence with the new ad1\nministration.\nHe is convinced that Secretary Tal\nwill be nominated by the Republican\nconvention at Chicago and will\nelected. He Is of course aware of th*\nmanner In which the charge lias bee\ncirculated that Taft would bo only\nRoosevelt man as president and thf\nwhatever Taft as president might fl\nit would le ascrllied to the Rooseve'i\ninfluence. Because of this situation\npurposes to take himself out of th\ncountry, where it will he impossible 1\nrepeat any such charge against Presi\ndent Taft. In other words, he intends\nto save both Taft and himself embar\nrassment.\nA confidential friend of President\nRoosevelt said the other day, In speal*\ning of the contemplated trip abroad:\nI have never heard the president\nsay it In so many words, but I am\nconvinced that he Is determined to give\nMr. Tnft an absolutely free hand. If\nMr. Roosevelt should remain in tilts\ncountry and be accessible to our clti\nsiens, everything that Mr. Taft would\ndo as president would be discussed\nwith relation to Roosevelt Politicians\ndesirous of reaching Taft would insist\nupon approaching Roosevelt. Because\nof the very intimate relations which\nhave existed between the president and\nsecretary of war the embarrassment\nwould be augmented. But after\nRoosevelt has been out of the country\nfor two years no such complication\nwould l\u00bbe possible.\"\nPersonally it will be much more sat\nisfactory to Mr. Roosevelt to be away\nfrom the country. If he wero to re\nmain here he would be subjected to\ngreat pressure from many men who\nthought htm under obligation to theui\nand who desire to obtain his Influence\nwith the new administration.\nMr. Roosevelt believes thoroughly In\nthe convention which makes it unbe\ncoming to an ex-president to prefer\na request to his successor. This is a\nconvention to which Mr. Cleveland has\nadhered strictly. Mr. Cleveland has\nwritten a few letters which have been\nused by their recipients in the effort\nto obtain some favors, but he has not\nmade a direct request He did not ask\nHarrison or McKinley for anything\nneither has he ever asked Mr. Itoose\nvelt for anything. Mr. Roosevelt as\nex-president will follow the tradition.\nIn traveling abroad Mr. Roosevelt\nwill not make any such tour as Gen\neral Grnnt did after retiring from the\npresidency. General Grant was re\nceived in state by emperors and kin\nwherever he went. He was feted as\nno other American ever has been. Mr\nRoosevelt will avoid all that, and by\nspending a good part of bis time In\npursuit of game he will put himself\nout of the way of social entertainment.\nSmoking Room In Women'i Club.\nA smoking room is being fitted up In\nthe women's clubhouse In East Orange,\nN. J. It will be ready for use next\nwinter. It will be furnished In mis\nsion style, with seats nil around the\nroom. The room is not for the women\nmembers, but for their men guests who\nattend concerts and dances In the club.\nThey have been deprived of this pleas\nure heretofore, Inasmuch as no smok\ning is permitted In other parti of tbe\nbuilding.\nMinnows to Fight Mosquitoes.\nAn attempt is being made at Tampa,\nFla., to rid the place of mosquitoes.\nWith that end in view n trio of fisher\nmen are engaged In catching minnows,\nwhich the chief of sanitation of the\ncity purposes distributing amoug the\ntanks and water receptacles In the resi\ndential and busiiie\u00ab portions of the\ncity. Severs! hundred minnows have\nalready been caught and will be util\nised for destroying the smbyro \u00abao*\nquito.\nONE WEAK SPOT\nMost Madison People Have\nWeak Part and too Often\nIt's the Back\nEveryone has a weak spot.\nToo often it's a bad l\u00bback.\nTwinges follow every sudden NfM\nDull aching keeps np, day and ttteht.\nTells you the kidneys need help.\nFor backache is really kidney-ache\nA kidney enre is what yon need.\nDoan's Kidney Pills cure sick kid\nneys.\nCure backache and all urinary ills.\nRobt. Wehlin, living on N. Nesmitn\nSt., Sioux Falls, 8. say: \"I have\nnot had occasion to use Doan's Kidney\nPills since I used tnein several yearn\nago. At that time my back was very\nweak and I had a constant pain across\nmy loins I was doing a great deal\nof heavy lifting and coDetant strait:\nupon my back seemed affect my ki*l\nneys. i procured a lox of Doan's Kid\nnev Pills at the Dunning Drng Co. and\nthe trouble entirely left me. I gave a\nstatement to this effect several yeai\nago and at this time, (Dec. 19. lit'iii\ncan recommend them just as highly\nI am very glad to say I have nut\nsuffered any recmrcnce of tbe com\nplaint.\"\nFor sale by all dealers. Price\n\"n\ncents. Foster-Millmrn Co., Buffalo.\nNew York, sole agents for the Unit\nStiites.\nRemember tbe\nn a e a n\ntake no other.\nScores of Settlers Threatened,\nDuluth, May 12.\u2014Forest fires arc\nthreatening scores of settlers' cabins\nin Northern Minnesota and are swoop\nir.g many square miles of territory\nMany of the fires have been started\nby careless fishermen. A rain storm\nnow prevailing may cheek their aci\nvance.\nPvjjTPGiairjipp\n^4\nlining 1 uincii i\u00bbio uiteii kiroi/\nsufferers for want of proper advice\nat just the right time.\nMrs. I'inkham, at Lynn, Mass.,has\nalways issued to young girls a soc\nial invitation to write to her al\u00bbout\ntheir sickness. She is a mother,\nand fully understands.\nIn nine chances out of ten your\ncase will In just the same as tho-r \u00bbf\nthe young ladies whose letters\nfollow.\nLTD!A F.PINKHAM'S\nVEGETABLE U0PPQUND\nis what you need to restore health.\nMiss Abby F. Harrows, of Nelson\nville, Ohio, writes to Mrs. Pinkham\nWhen I wrote to you I was very\nnervous, had dull headaches, backache,\nand was very irregular. Doctors did me\nno good. Lydia E. Piukham's Vegetable\nCompound and your advice made me\nregular, well and strong. I am now in\nbetter health thau ever before.\"\nMiss Elsie L. Hook, of Chelsea,\nVt., writes to Mrs. l'inkham:\nI am only sixteen years old, but\nLydia E. Pinkham's Vegetable Com\npound and your advice have cured me\nof sideache, periodic pains, and a ner\nvous, irritable condition after every\nthing else had failed.\"\nFACTS FOR SICK WOMEN.\nFor thirty years Lydia K rink\nham's Vegetable Comjxmnd, made\nfrom roots and herbs, has leen the\nstandard remedy for female ills,\nand has positively cured thousands of\nwomen who have been troubled with\ndisplacements, inflammation, ulcera\ntion, fibroid tumors, irregularities,\nperiodic pains, backache, that bear-,\ning-down feeling, flatulency,indiges\ntion,dizziness,or nervous prostration.\nWhy don't you try it\nQAl\ni\n&\u00a3LYi\nfgtoJOR \u00a3\u00b0VS\nELY\ns\nI'asy\nCough Caution\nWv. r. ri*i-:rn\n1\nsoothe,\nand\n\u2022iiuai.-\nTown\nCREAM BALM\nSure to G